# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fly-io
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fly-io/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:fly-io/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:fly-io/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:fly-io/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:fly-io/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:fly-io/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:fly-io/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:fly-io/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:fly-io/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:fly-io/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:fly-io/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:fly-io/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:fly-io/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:fly-io/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:fly-io/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:fly-io/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:fly-io/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:fly-io/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:fly-io/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:fly-io/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:fly-io/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:fly-io/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:fly-io/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:fly-io/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:fly-io/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:fly-io/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:fly-io/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:fly-io/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:fly-io/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:fly-io/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:fly-io/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:fly-io/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:fly-io/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:fly-io/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:fly-io/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:fly-io/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:fly-io/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:fly-io/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
